<p align="center"><font color="#0E024D" face="Arial"><strong>PLAYER SUBMITTED STRATEGY</strong></font></p>
<div align="center"><center>

  <div align="center"><center><table border="0" width="90%">
    <tr>
      <td>
      <center><font face="Arial"><strong><b><font color="#800000">HARMONY TACTICS</b></font> - <small>Auzumel, Rodcet Nife</small></strong></font><font face="Arial"></center>
<div align="center"><center>
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td>
    <small><hr size="1" color="#C0C0C0"><P>
    At level 5, every druid gets Harmony.  It's an incredible spell!  You can easily use it well into your 20s and beyond, if you find the right situations.  If you aren't using it, you're just making your life soooooo much harder.<P>

First, Harmony lets you take ANY camp.  ANY!  It makes you a huge asset to any group that wants to work 1 or more camps. <P> 

First, find a group.  You need at least one other person if the camp you're considering may have yellows.  Personally, I always like a ranger because between spawns that ranger can bring to you the best of the wondering beasties as well.  I like 3 person groups best, because your chances of surviving uninvited guests jumps up incredibly.  At this point, any caster (especially one with a pet) is a good choice for that third slot.  Remember, a group cuts down on downtime--so build a group with that in mind--smallish and efficient.<P>

Now--start looking for a camp that nobody mucks with because it's a little too far from zone or has a few too many beasties in it.  You don't have to worry--you have Harmony.  Lesser Fay and Rathe Mountains are full of choices--and just about every other outdoor zone beyond the newbie areas has a few.  <P>

Camo yourself and scout the camp.  You're going to need to cast Harmony on each foe except the first one you plan to pull.  Find the place you can stand and target the most foes to begin.  Harmony those.  Now approach (you can walk right up to the ones you've Harmonied) and Harmony the others.  Always play it safe--don't get any closer than you have to.  Take your time.  Don't try this while the camp is respawning--you're actually safer with a full camp that you know than a half-empty camp where a new mob may spawn on top of you while you're Harmonizing another. <P>

I suggest you Harmony all the foes in a camp.  You can depend on the AE effect to keep you safe--but the full Harmony on each assures your safety.  Pull the one you want--it's best to pull one that does not have to run past others--so pull from the outside and work further in as you go.  Here's the marvel.  After you pull the first foe and finish it, ANY one of your group can walk up to the next target, hit it and run--pulling ONLY that foe.  All the others are contemplating the beauty of peace, love and nature or whatever and just can't be bothered to assist. <P> 

It won't take you and your group long to get a feel for how fast they can clear the camp and what they can handle.  You'll be churning through that camp and the only downtime will be waiting for spawn--even with yellows.  (That's why a ranger is so nice!  "Hey!  Can you bring us a big ol' spider?  I need silk.")<P>

Some rules of thumb:<P>

Remember that Harmony is AE and has a good long duration.  However, newly spawned creatures and wanderers are not under the effect until you specifically cast it on them.  These are the foes that can make your pulls go badly.  The better you know an area, the more safe your pulls will be.  Warn your group that wierd things can happen.<P>  

And, if you end up with the whole camp on your tail due to an EXTREMELY RARE resist or to a wanderer rousing the camp, do not drag certain death back to your group.  Run to a nice place away from camp and from your group, type loc so you can find your corpse and die like a good soldier. <P> 

To better understand Harmony:
Cast Harmony on yourself and watch how long it lasts.  Heck--look at the clock!  It's a long time for a lulling spell--a very long time.  During that duration, only a direct attack or a call for assist practically on top of them will cause a foe to aggro.  Now--the AE is trickier to figure.  Try casting on a non-agro creature in the newbie fields at different distances away--if it is close enough, you will be harmonized too.  That way, you can check how big the AE effect is.  (Actually, pretty darn large.)  If you have a good head for things like distances, you can use the AE to minimize the number of times you need to cast Harmony on a single camp.<P>

Have fun!  Be a hero to your group with Harmony and advance quickly while you collect great riches as well.  


		
    </small></font></p>
    <p><small><font face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></small></td>
